05359nam a22009135i 9783110580761DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019949155  a97831105807617 a10.1515/97831105807612doi  a(DE-B1597)490074  a(OCoLC)1132419373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN1995.9.A8bL4413 2020 4aPN1995.9.A8bL4413 2020 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a791.430192231 aLehmann, Hauke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAffect Poetics of the New Hollywood :bSuspense, Paranoia, and Melancholy /cHauke Lehmann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 276 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCinepoetics – English edition ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Splitting the Spectator -- t2 Suspense: Forms of Cinematic Thinking -- t3 Paranoia: Forms of Mediatization -- t4 Melancholy: Ways of Perceiving History -- t5 A History of Feeling -- tList of figures -- tBibliography -- tSubject index -- tName index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is affective experience produced in the cinema? And how can we write a history of this experience? By asking these questions, this study by Hauke Lehmann aims at rethinking our conception of a critical period in US film history – the New Hollywood: as a moment of crisis that can neither be reduced to economic processes of adaption nor to a collection of masterpieces. Rather, the fine-grained analysis of core films reveals the power of cinematic images to affect their audiences – to confront them with the new. The films of the New Hollywood redefine the divisions of the classical genre system in a radical way and thereby transform the way spectators are addressed affectively in the cinema. The study describes a complex interplay between three modes of affectivity: suspense, paranoia, and melancholy. All three, each in their own way, implicate spectators in the deep-seated contradictions of their own feelings and their ways of being in the world: their relations to history, to society, and to cultural fantasy. On this basis, Affect Poetics of the New Hollywood projects an original conception of film history: as an affective history which can be re-written up to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMotion picture audiencesxPsychology. 0aMotion picturesxPsychological aspects. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican film history.  aCinematic affect.  aaesthetic experience.  acinematic temporality.1 aLattimer, James.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831105797270 cprintz978311057960440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311058076140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110580761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110580761.jpg  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBO